		<item>
			<title>Apostolos Doxiadis</title>
			<link>http://www.logicomix.com/en/index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=78:apostolos-doxiadis&amp;catid=37:the-team&amp;Itemid=18</link>
			<guid>http://www.logicomix.com/en/index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=78:apostolos-doxiadis&amp;catid=37:the-team&amp;Itemid=18</guid>
			<description><![CDATA[<p><a target="_self" href="http://www.logicomix.com/en/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=78:2008-12-29-09-33-25&catid=37:2008-12-26-20-19-16&Itemid=18"><img src="http://www.logicomix.com/en/images/stories/theTeam/team1-small.jpg" alt="team1-small" style="float: left;" height="98" width="98" /></a><span style="font-size: 11pt;"><span style="color: #993300;"><a href="http://www.logicomix.com/en/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=78:2008-12-29-09-33-25&catid=37:2008-12-26-20-19-16&Itemid=18">Apostolos Doxiadis</a></span></span><span style="color: #993300;"> <span style="color: #000000;">-</span> </span>concept, story and script<br /><br />Apostolos studied mathematics, but later repented and became a writer.  His novel <em>Uncle Petros and Goldbach’s Conjecture</em> has been translated into over 30 different languages and is widely considered to be the trendsetting book in “mathematical fiction”. While he’s tried his hand in various storytelling media, Apostolos is unfortunately totally unmusical.</p>
]]></description>
			<author>info@intelweb.gr (Vaggelis)</author>
